In the desperate world of modern dating, scouring OKCupid and Tinder is an exhausting quest to find a potential match-up that is terribly unsettling. It can sometimes approach the level of a strangely coercive job interview, where you must advertise yourself in the interest of an illusory mutual attraction. This process of curating the ideal “you” can sometimes feel like fabricating a very specific fiction: a romantic-social construct to represent you based solely on selectively chosen ideals.

We see this everywhere. Advertisement The fetishization of the faux-personality was brought to media one-to-one attention recently by Girls star Alex Karpovsky’s movie Red Flag. In one scene, Karpovsky’s character goes on a date with a woman and asks her what movies she likes, and at one point, pulls out his laptop to show her his personal movie collection you can literally see four movie posters above his bed.

The woman says something like, “That’s OK, I like movies too! And it feels kind of unfair of me to suggest that a male view of the femme flicks wouldn’t be credible, but that “I like movies, too, women,” charade usually feels totally disingenuous on a date. Probably because it is. I’ve certainly been guilty of playing the pretend-nonchalant film buff who likes movies
